<p><b>Thomas Gold</b> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1920-05-22"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="05-22"><a href="/wiki/May_22" title="May 22">May 22</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1920" title="1920">1920</a></span> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2004-06-22"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="06-22"><a href="/wiki/June_22" title="June 22">June 22</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2004" title="2004">2004</a></span>) was an <a href="/wiki/Austria" title="Austria">Austrian</a> born <a href="/wiki/Astrophysicist" title="Astrophysicist" class="mw-redirect">astrophysicist</a>, a professor of <a href="/wiki/Astronomy" title="Astronomy">astronomy</a> at <a href="/wiki/Cornell_University" title="Cornell University">Cornell University</a>, a member of the U.S. <a href="/wiki/United_States_National_Academy_of_Sciences" title="United States National Academy of Sciences">National Academy of Sciences</a>, and a Fellow of the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Society" title="Royal Society">Royal Society</a> (London). Gold was one of three young <a href="/wiki/University_of_Cambridge" title="University of Cambridge">Cambridge</a> scientists who in the 1950s proposed the now mostly abandoned <a href="/wiki/Steady_state_theory" title="Steady state theory" class="mw-redirect">'steady state'</a> hypothesis of the <a href="/wiki/Universe" title="Universe">universe</a>. Gold's work crossed academic and scientific boundaries, into <a href="/wiki/Biophysics" title="Biophysics">biophysics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Astrophysics" title="Astrophysics">astrophysics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Aerospace_engineering" title="Aerospace engineering">space engineering</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Geophysics" title="Geophysics">geophysics</a>.</p>
